observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:
a. Municipal Accountant to make representation with LBP, DBP and PNB in determining the significant discrepancies recorded in the bank versus their records to reconcile with the correct balances;
b. Acting Municipal Treasurer to carefully examine the documents of the ₱5,250.00 charged to PNB-GF and imposed sanctions to those who allowed for the said transactions, otherwise, the Audit Team will issue Notice of Disallowance;
c. Management to replenish the amount of ₱1,899,000.00 from PVB-GF to PNB-GF for the erroneous charging of disbursements;
d. Municipal Accountant to properly account deposits based on validated deposit slips and not on the balance of un-deposited collections; and
e. Municipal Accountant to effect the PAJE.

We recommended that the management:
a. update the conduct of the physical inventory of all properties of the LGU annually and submit annual physical inventory report of Property Plant and Equipment;
b. ensure that all properties of the municipality issued to officer and employees shall be covered by Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR), which shall be renewed every January of the third year after issue; 
c. require the Accounting Department to maintain a separate updated subsidiary ledgers of property plant and equipment to support the general ledger accounts to ensure completeness of the recorded amounts in the books of accounts; and
d. require the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain property cards and reconcile regularly with the accounting records.

We recommended that:
a. The Municipal Treasurer submit the disbursements vouchers pertaining to the unaccounted and unreported disbursements of ₱8,780,198.19 to the Municipal Accountant;
b. The Municipal Accountant ensure that all disbursement vouchers are valid, authorized and duly supported with documents, them in the book of accounts and submit them to the Auditor, otherwise same will be disallowed in audit;
c. Henceforth, the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant ensure timely submission of all paid vouchers to the offices concerned for accounting, recording and for post audit purposes.

We recommended and Management agreed to strictly follow the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances by:
a. not granting additional cash advances to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him is settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;
b. not granting cash advances to elected officials and to employees who are not bonded/designated as disbursing officer for purposes other than their travelling expenses;
c. not granting cash advances other than those allowed under COA Circular 97-002;
d. notifying the concerned officials and employees of their accountabilities and demand for the immediate settlement of their outstanding Cash advances, including imposing sanctions or withholding of salaries in case of non-compliance, pursuant to the provisions of paragraph 9.3.2 and other pertinent provision of COA Circular No. 97-002;
e. verifying, validating documents, and ascertaining that all liquidation documents are signed before accepting, recording and forwarding them to COA for post audit; and
f. submitting liquidation reports of cash advances within the prescribed period as required under paragraph 5 of the said COA circular.

We recommended that the management:
a. submit justification or basis in computing wages and ACA/PERA of casual employees at fixed 22 working days a month, otherwise;
b. deduct from the accumulated leaves of casual employees, the number of days equivalent to the amount of over payment they received, otherwise, require corresponding refund;
c. comply with the provisions of DBM Manual on Position Classification and Compensation and Budget Circular 2009-003 for the computation of casual employees’ wages and ACA/PERA, respectively;
d. submit/attach to the payroll, the approved daily time records of the casual employees to ascertain the actual work days rendered.

We commended the organized and properly maintained Temporary Residual Containment Area (TRCA) and construction of sound and spacious septic vault. However, we recommended that management:
a. Implement the LGU programs and activities for ecological solid waste management as planned/programmed for the benefits of its constituent;
b. Strengthen the Information, Education and Communication program on proper waste disposal and ecological solid waste management program of the LGU;
c. Consider establishing Temporary Containment Area in far flung barangays to be hauled periodically or as needed due to inaccessibility and to lessen hauling expenses.

We recommended, and management agreed to comply with the pertinent provision of Section 344 of RA 7160, section 52 and section 18 of NGAS for Local Volume I and II, respectively by requiring:
a. the Issuance of obligation request for contract and other transactions at gross before payment. No further obligation request needed during progress billing/partial payment;
b. the issuance of obligation request for cash advances at gross before payment. If the liquidation does not equal to the cash advance, issue separate obligation request to adjust the difference accordingly;
c. the Accounting section maintain separate registries for appropriation, allotment and obligation to be reconciled with the budget office registries every end of the month or as necessary; and
d. obligation of allotment by certifying/approving and recording the Obligation Request to the appropriate registries to earmark the allotment, safe from being misappropriated to other activities, program or project.

